Under optimal experimental conditions (pH 7.0 and the incubation time 40 min, the detailed analysis date was shown in Figs. S5A and B), the sensitivity of the developed PAD was studied by incubation with a series of OTA concentrations. As shown in the inset of Fig. 4
                        A, the corresponding current intensity increased gradually with the increasing concentrations of OTA in the range from 100 fg mL−1 to 200 ng mL−1. This is attributed to the successful formation of apta1-OTA-apta2 sandwich-type structure, and the more Ch-MoS2-Au@Pt bound to the sensing interface via DNA hybridization, resulting in catalytic decomposition of H2O2 and a corresponding stronger electrochemical signal. The good linear relationship between the electrochemical response and the logarithm of OTA concentration could be obtained, and the calibration equations were Ι = 8.25lgC+85.35 (R2 = 0.9978). In addition, the ultralow limit of detection (LOD) of OTA was calculated to be 25.2 fg mL−1 on the basis of S/N = 3, which was superior to that in previously reported sensors (Table 1
                        ).
